<article>
    <h1>SOCHI URINE SAM&#xAD;PLES TO BE TESTED AGAIN</h1>
    <h2>Agency to ex&#xAD;tend re&#xAD;anal&#xAD;y&#xAD;sis to all sports and na&#xAD;tion&#xAD;al&#xAD;i&#xAD;ties in&#xAD;volved in 2014 Win&#xAD;ter Games</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201211/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-11"><time>2020-12-11</time></a>
        - <span>SPORT</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>LAU­SANNE • Urine sam­ples col­lected at the Sochi Win­ter Olympic Games in 2014 are to be re­anal­ysed in a fur­ther bid to crack down on dop­ing cheats, the In­ter­na­tional Test­ing Agency (ITA) an­nounced on Wed­nes­day.</p>
    <p>The ITA said its aim was to com­plete the Sochi re­anal­y­sis pro­gramme, in­clud­ing the han­dling of the re­sult­ing cases, be­fore the 2022 Win­ter Olympics in Bei­jing.</p>
    <p>“After se­ri­ous is­sues of ma­nip­u­la­tion of the dop­ing con­trol process came to light fol­low­ing the Sochi Games, the IOC (In­ter­na­tional Olympic Com­mit­tee) al­ready re­ex­am­ined hun­dreds of sam­ples from par­tic­i­pat­ing Rus­sian ath­letes in 2016,” the agency added.</p>
    <p>“The ITA will now ex­tend the re­anal­y­sis pro­gramme to all na­tion­al­i­ties and sports that took part in the event and retest more than half of the to­tal sam­ples col­lected as a first step.”</p>
    <p>Un­der the World Anti-Dop­ing Code, sam­ples can be stored for up to 10 years after their ini­tial anal­y­sis and still re­tain the same le­gal im­pact if retested and pros­e­cuted.</p>
    <p>The ITA said in­creased anti- dop­ing in­tel­li­gence across var­i­ous sports and re­cent an­a­lyt­i­cal ad­vances, “es­pe­cially re­gard­ing the trac­ing of steroids and hor­mones”, would en­able it to iden­tify un­de­tected dop­ing violations “that may have oc­curred at Sochi 2014”.</p>
    <p>The IOC brought in the ITA, which operates as an in­de­pen­dent or­gan­i­sa­tion con­duct­ing anti- dop­ing pro­grammes for more than 45 in­ter­na­tional fed­er­a­tions and ma­jor event or­gan­is­ers, to take on its anti-dop­ing pro­gramme in 2018.</p>
    <p>The fur­ther anal­y­sis of sam­ples col­lected dur­ing Bei­jing 2008 and Lon­don 2012, the ITA said, has so far pro­duced more than 130 an­ti­dop­ing rule violations, which “clearly high­lights the ef­fec­tive­ness of such a pro­gramme in the de­tec­tion and de­ter­rence of cheat­ing”.</p>
    <p>Sochi 2014 has been tainted after hosts Rus­sia’s state-spon­sored dop­ing pro­gramme was ex­posed.</p>
    <p>This in­cluded the wide­spread swop­ping of con­tam­i­nated sam­ples for clean ones, a prac­tice con­firmed by the for­mer head of the Moscow Anti-Dop­ing Lab­o­ra­tory turned whis­tle-blower Grig­ory Rod­chenkov.</p>

